                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding>
                                <p> Contemporary binding from Vadstena, made after 1450. White leather over wooden boards. 3 double bands and endbands. Hook-clasp fastening, catchplate on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>. Pastedowns missing, remains of text offset on the wooden boards on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, in red ink: <quote>E III xi in ordine</quote>. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, in brown ink: <quote>CC</quote>; in brown ink: <quote>85</quote>; stamped in gold: <quote>A 22</quote>; remains of old label, partially illegible, in black ink: <quote>18.</quote>, <quote>A. 22</quote>.</p>
                                <p> Regarding the binding and dating see <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107119">Lindberg (1977)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="128" to="128" unit="column"/>
                                    </bibl>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="300" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="230" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="50" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="images">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> is decorated in ink, a double frame drawn in ink and inside it a thick cross. <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/> is also decorated with a double frame which contains two thin cross-like shapes (possibly later additions). The clasp is decorated with red leather.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather dirty and torn. Boards, the folded leather covering, threads, and attachment straps visible on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100081">Sweden</placeName>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100101">Vadstena</placeName>
                                </origPlace>
                                <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1401">15th century, first half</origDate>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The manuscript belonged to library in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100101">Vadstena</placeName> (see shelf mark on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>). In <date when="1620"/> the manuscript was transferred to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100010">National Archives</orgName> by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100544">Johannes Bureus</persName>, see <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107135">Gödel (1916)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="283" to="286" unit="page">Appendix 2 and 3</citedRange>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Later the manuscript was transferred to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName> and is listed in its inventories and catalogues. There are 4 unique signa on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, 3 of which have been identified.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The older signum, <quote>85</quote>, is mentioned in the inventory from 1722 (U 90:4, p. 42).</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Current signum, <quote>A 22</quote>, was first established in Helin’s catalogue from the 1720’s (U 91:2:2).</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Shelfmark at the National Archives (from the 19th century): <quote>18</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>From the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archives</orgName> to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> in <date when="1780"/>. In <date when="1889"/> to the <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100069">National Archives</placeName>, but returned to the National Library in <date when="1909"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
